<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Eriogonum fasciculatum </i>is a semi-woody, many-branching shrub up to 1.5 m tall with woody, many-branched roots to 1.5 m in depth. Plants often occur on coarse-textured soils that may be moderately saline. Plants lose some leaves in the dry season and most in severe drought, and they turn reddish in color. Plants flower from early spring through summer. Seeds are dispersed by ants, wind, and water. Seed germination requires light, and seedling success is high in wet years (Montalvo 2002b). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Salvia apiana </i>is a rounded shrub up to 2.5 m tall with roots to 1.5 m in depth. Shrubs have aromatic, whitish to pale gray-green leaves that persist throughout the year. Seeds are dispersed by gravity, harvester ants, and seed-caching rodents. Seedlings emerge in the cool season and take 2 years or more to reach maturity. Seedling establishment in shrublands is associated with gaps among the shrubs. Shrubs often sprout following fire from basal burls, but year-old seedlings are killed by fire. Repeated burning kills mature plants. Seedlings emerge from the seed bank in the first season after fire, but reported densities are low. High-intensity fires kill seeds (Montalvo 2002c). <br/>
<br/>
This alliance is locally common in southwestern California. It is characteristic of hot, dry summer conditions and is most abundant away from the immediate coast where fog is not usually present. It is usually found at low to moderate elevations on south-facing slopes adjacent to chaparral. The lack of variation at the association level, despite a large sampling of the alliance’s distribution, suggests it is a simple and relatively homogeneous vegetation type. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
