<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text">Both <i>Eriogonum fasciculatum </i>and <i>Salvia apiana </i>sprout after fire, but most shrub regeneration is from buried seed after fire for <i>Eriogonum fasciculatum </i>(Keeley 1998a). Stands usually return after low-intensity and lower-frequency fires, primarily by seeding and by some sprouting. However, frequent fires can deplete the seed bank for shrubs while the seed bank for exotic species can increase (Giessow and Zedler 1996, Minnich 1988), making stands vulnerable to local extinction.</div>
	<table class="zebraStripe">
		
		<tr>
			<td class="key">Fire return interval</td>
			<td>Medium (15-70+ years)
				
			</td>
		</tr>
		
		<tr>
			<td class="key">Seasonality</td>
			<td>Late summer-fall
				
			</td>
		</tr>
		
