    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Ba-b, Bd-g, Bi). Stands in Santa Monica Mountains occur on dry ridgetops, generally inland from the coast and above the summer inversion layer (Keeler-Wolf and Evens 2006).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Ba-d, Bf-g, Bi-p). Stands exist generally for low elevations, especially in the Peninsular Ranges (Gordon and White 1994, Evens and San 2005, Klein and Evens 2005) and west to the desert edges in Anza-Borrego Desert State Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998b).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Eriogonum fasciculatum </i>and <i>Salvia apiana </i>are decreasing in wildlands with increased fire frequency, the presence of non-native grasses, and air pollution. Successful restoration requires conditions where shrubs can establish, mature, and develop seed banks (Montalvo 2002c). </div>
</div>

    

    

